### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh‚Äôs mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input:The sanctions against the school were a punishing blow, and they seemed to what the efforts the school had made to change? Choices:  A: ignore B: enforce C: authoritarian D: yell at E: avoid<n>Output:		A<n><n>Input: The company tried to come up with a plan of action, hoping that they could use their best judgment to solve the issue with a minimum of damage. Choices:  A) compassion B ) censure C) contempt D) cost E) conflict<n>Output: A<n>

Choices:  A: hospital B: head C: sick person D: elderly person E: doctor's office<n>Output:		A<n><n># Tutoring<n>## What is a word problem?<n>Word problems require  the knowledge and strategies of arithmetic operations as well as an understanding of the meaning of words. <n>Word problems may ask students to identify missing numbers in a sum or difference situation.<n>Word problems may call on students to understand rate of change, multiplication and  division as they work with problems asking for missing quantities. <n>Questions asking students to interpret word problems may require them to know how to calculate area, perimeter, length or some other measure.<n>For example, say your teacher asks "How much paper is used to cover this floor? What must be determined? How many floor squares fit into a piece of paper? <n>What operation is used?  How much does it cost?<n><n>### Ways to simplify word problems<n>**Try to break the problem into component parts**.  For instance, "Dave baked and ate 1/8 of a 10 pound pie." <n>What do you know? <n>You know that 1/8 of the pie is a piece of pie and that it cost Dave 1/10 of the pie.  This problem is not too difficult because Dave ate 1/5 of the pie and the pie weighed ten pounds. <n>**Reexamine the word problem**.  To determine the length of the river, first determine the size of the river and then determine its depth.  To find the depth, multiply the width by 6.  Therefore, the length is 540 feet.<n>**Make the problem more concrete to help the student better grasp the problem**.  For example, a student may be given the problem "If 400 gallons of paint can be used on 3 buildings at 2 hours, how much can be used on one building in five hours?"  <n>The problem can be presented differently:  A man wants to paint his barn in five hours.  If it takes six hours to paint a roof and three hours to paint a garage,  how many hours does it take to paint the barn? <n><n># Ways to solve word problems<n>**Understand the different ways in which a problem can be expressed in word problem**.   For example, an expression such as "2x + 3" can be expressed algebraically as "2x = 3 + x" or "x +

How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. Too many students just write down all of the given facts without understanding what to do with them or what the answer would look like. It is a common problem that many 7th grade students encounter‚Äîthey don‚Äôt understand the connection between the question being asked and the answer being sought. The challenge is getting them to look beyond the immediate facts and consider what would happen instead.<n><n>### Question Answer:<n><n>Output: A, This question tests a 7th grader's understanding of division with remainders. 7th grade is the first time that multiple numbers can be involved in division and the resulting answer will have a remainder. This is a question about the student's understanding that the numbers don't end. Choices:  A: demonstration B: conference C: building D: garage E: mouth<n>Output:		garage<n><n><n># Question 1: How much does it cost to get 9999 99? <n><n>You spend one thousand dollars to get 99 cents. If you have 60,000 dollars and you want to spend 79,999.99, how much money do you have left? <n><n># Answer:<n><n>**It costs 79,000 dollars to get 79,980.19** <n><n># Question 2: For which of the following, would you need to calculate the perimeter?<n><n>##### a. A table<n>##### b. A room<n>##### c. A football field<n>##### d. A bookcase<n><n># Answer: (c)<n>##### a. Perimeter of a table <n><n>The table will have 4 sides like 1 side of a square. <n>If you have 2 sides of each table, you would get a value of 4 times 2. <n><n>So, 4 * 2 would be 8. <n>##### b. Perimeter of a room <n><n>If you add the length and the width of a room, you would get that perimeter. <n><n>##### c. Perimeter of a football field <n><n>You will need to calculate the perimeters of a rectangular shape. <n><n>The length of the field would be 80 yards and the width of the field would be also 80 yards. <n><n>So you have 160 yards of perimeter. <n>##### d. Perimeter of a bookcase <n><n>The length is 0.5 m and the width is 1.5 meters. <n><n>The area would be 2 * 1.5 = 3, but you should not calculate the area of a bookcase, but its perimeter. <n>So 3 + 2 = 5 for the perimeter of the length and the width. <n>#####<n><n>**Explanation 1:**<n><n>For this question, you will need the right unit that measures distance. <n>You will then be able to calculate the perimeter value for each image. <n>The answers will be in meters in the first and second image, but the meters are equivalent to the yards for the second and third images.
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input:How can one's views change after learning about science? Choices:  A: appreciation of nature B: become educated C: excitement D: increased knowledge E: see things differently<n>Output:		E<n><n>### Solutions:<n><n>* Mary has 89 stickers left. If she used 3 large stickets and 7 stickers for the each of 6 pages, she had used a total of 51 small stickers. Therefore, she has 49 - 51 = 49 + 89 - 51 stickers left which is 49 + 38, which is 89 = 87.<n>* Zach will have 6*2 + $ 10 - $ 5 = 70 + $ 5 = 80 $.<n>* Mark has 23 kangs and 3 kangs * 4 goats =12 goats which are 23*4 + 12.<n>* Josh has 20 - 12 = 10 $.<n>* George's bowling score should be 287 * 12 = 3444 which is 287.<n>* Max spent 1/6 - 2x1/2 + 3x1/3 + 60 minutes on homework.<n>* Sophia ate 240.<n>* Each person needs to contribute 21$.<n>* Tom's dog will be 12*6 = 72 years.<n><n>#### 4.13: Write a Python script to convert temperature from Celsius to Fahrenheit and Fahrenheit to Celsius.<n>```<n>Celsius to Fahreneheit:<n>Celsius = Celsius * 9 / 5 + 32<n>Farenheit to Celsius:<n>Farenheit = Farenheit - 32 * 5 / 9<n>```<n>

How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh‚Äôs mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input:If you've thrown a rod you've done damage to what? Choices:  A: cross street B: stand upright C: speak spanish D: speak chinese E: further education<n>Output:		E<n><n># Program: C++<n># Author: Chris M<n><n>class Solution {<n>public:<n>    int getStickers(int Mary, int largeStickers, int stickersPerPage){<n>        return Mary - largeStickers + stickersPerPage*6;<n>    }<n>    <n>    int getMoney(int Zach, int weeklyAllowance, int extraDollars){<n>        return Zach + weeklyAllowance + extraDollars - 65;<n>    }<n>   <n>    int getLegs(int Mark, int kangaroos, int goats){<n>        return kangaroos*2 + 3*goats;<n>    }<n><n>    int getMalls(int Josh, int money, int dollarsForEachCookie){<n>        return 20*dollarsForEachCookie - dollarsForEachCookie;<n>    }<n> <n>    int getPoints(int George, int teamAverage, int rounds){ <n>        return 287*(rounds-(teamAverage / 287)) ;<n>    }<n> 	<n>    int getMinsDoingHW(int Max, int biology, int history, int geography):<n>        return timeTaken(biology*2, history*2, geography*3);<n> <n>    int gramsPie(int Sophia, int grams, int pieWeight):<n>        return pieWeight-(pieWeight/6)*Sophia;<n>    <n>    int ContributeBill(int Sarah, int Mary, int Tuan, int cost, int ):<n>        return cost/3;<n>    <n>    long getSonAge(int Tom, int brother):<n>        return 30*(1+4*6);<n> 	<n>    char ability(int):<n>		if(E)<n>		    {<n>			    return 'E';<n>		    }  <n>};<n><n># Program: Java<n><n>public class Problem32_37 {<n>	public static void main(String[] args) {<n>		Solution mySolution = new Solution();		<n>		mySolution.problem32("89", "3", "7");<n>		mySolutions.problem33("Zach", "5", "10");<n>

I used half for my x value and that was a key to find the solution.<n><n>3) In first function I took 25 minutes and on second I used 8 minutes.<n><n>4) On the fourth function, I changed the time to 25 minutes. However, If you want to get a better result then change your time to 15 to 20 minutes.<n><n>

The Foundning Fathers<n><n>### Notes<n><n>I had my first Python coding interview today using a python lens to solve common programming problems asked in Python interviews. Overall, it went great and the majority of the questions asked were pretty common, straight forward, relatively easy questions. For those unfamiliar with an "interviewing lens", these are sets of online coding platforms to practice a programming language's typical interview questions to help students prepare and practice before any future interviewing process. In the case of Python, the main platform I found on Amazon is Python Lens while there are other platforms such as Leetcode for specific programming solutions.<n><n>Overall, my results are satisfactory at this time as I was able to get all the answers correctly. However, there is only one section that I struggled with in which was the logic puzzles I have shared as I need to improve upon my logic and reasoning skills. <n><n>### Resources<n><n>The main references I used were the Leetcode Problem Solver and Coursera's Algorithms and Data Structures Course. The reason I am mentioning these two as they helped me to learn Python fundamentals and the algorithms and data structures most important in coding as well as to help me find the solutions to certain problems I had in coding prior to this coding interview.<n>

Choices:  A: downtown area B: container C: ocean floor D: the lost city of atlantis E: high school<n>Output:		downtown area<n>```<n><n>We noticed that the number of multiple choice questions, given to students, was increasing drastically, as the semester progressed.  In this lesson, we'll be doing the same set of problems for multiple weeks, but use a different format depending on the week.  Sometimes, the questions we'll have will be multiple choice, and sometimes they'll be word problems.<n><n>### Objectives: By the end of this class you should be able to<n><n>- Solve for the unknown variable in multiple choice problems that ask for the same operation to be done to each number within the problem except for the variable<n><n>---<n><n>### What's the question? <n><n>The question is "Which operation do I need to do to find this variable?  Do I need to add or do I need to subtract?"<n><n>---<n><n>When you're solving for a variable, and the problem describes a different operation that needs to happen to different numbers throughout the problem, except for the variable<n>- You're going to have to do that same operation to all of the other numbers, except for your variable, in order to find the variable<n>- If you do that operation, and your variable makes a number larger, it's a subtract<n>- If you do the operation, and your variable make the number smaller, it needs to be an add<n>- So, if we take all of those numbers over there, we've got 7 + 3 = X, and then we also have 8 + 2 = X<n>- Well, if we do 7 + 3, it's not going to make this 10 larger since we're already at 10.  <n>- Therefore, we've got to subtract<n>- If we did 3 - 7, it would've made it smaller, so we've gotta add<n>- If you go 8 + 2 makes it even bigger.  So, I've got to do<n>- Anything I do here, it should be an add, because it'll make it bigger<n>- Anything over here, you'd have to do the opposite, since it'd be smaller<n><n>### How to find the correct path in between weeks<n><n>When deciding to do either multiple choice quizzes or word problems, students can use last week's quiz

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh‚Äôs mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input:Where can the legs of a stool be built? Choices:  A: jail B: internet cafe C: blacksmith's shop D: building E: bar<n>Output:		B<n><n># Question 1<n><n>## Answer: Mary has 44 stickers remaining<n><n>```python<n>>>> mary = 89<n>>>> large = 3<n>>>> medium = 7<n>>>> page = 6<n>>>> stickers = mary - (large * page) - (medium * (page + 1))<n>>>> stickers<n>44<n>```<n><n>## Detailed explanation:<n><n>### Let's first convert the stickers to an integer using int(). Converting Mary to an integer is necessary because she's a human and humans have fractions, thus making it harder to calculate her stickers. The first line converts the total amount of stickers Mary has, 89, into an integer.<n><n>### Next we have our large stickers. We want to use these stickers to cover the first page of journal that is front so we want the amount of large stickers to be multiplied by the number of front page journal and assigned to the variable that is 'front' in this case, using the asterisk symbol *<n><n>In this case, the amount of large sticklers is 3. The number of sticklers on the front page however, is 1. We subtract out the following line. We can see that the result is in negative which is correct.<n><n>### Then we have the medium sticklers. We want to use this to paste 7 sticklers on 6 pages, therefore we need to keep multiplying the number of medium sticklers (which are 7), by the number of pages that we want to paste the sticklers on +1, which is 6 + 1. What we are adding here is an extra page for the last page that can be pasted with a medium sticker. We assign that amount to the variable 'page'.<n><n>### Then, we subtract out the 7 * 6 + 1 result and assign it to a variable, which is 'page'.<n><n>We can see that there is the amount of medium sticklers remaining in the first page and then the amount of it left from the last page. We subtract the first from the second to get the amount of medium stickers remaining.<n><n>## Lastly we can add them together to get the answer.<n><n>## Question 2<n><n>## Answer: Zach needs $6 more<n><n>```python<n># Convert total allowance

His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh‚Äôs mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh‚Äôs mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input:what do you do before going to party? Choices:  A: call 911 B: enjoy yourself C: get drunk D: having sex E: meet new people<n>Output:		1<n><n>- [ ] 1, 2, 3, 4<n>- [x] True <n>- [ ] False<n><n># Output explanation:<n># 1. 39 + 46 = 89 + 3 + 7 x 6 = 89 - 39 = 44<n># 2. Zach needs to earn 10 dollars from today (already has $65) for the total amount to be 100.<n># 3. m = 5, n = 23 + (3*m) = 23 + 3*5 = 23 +15 = 38, legs = (2*m) + (4*n) = 2*23 + 4*38 = 46+152 =198<n># 4. money left = 20 - 10 + 2 - 4(1.25) = 8 - 1 = 7<n># 5. Average = (287*10 + X)/4X = 2870 + 1X/4 = 287 + 1X/3 <n><n># 6. Max's time = 20/2*1 + 20/1*3 = 20/3 = 6.666 minutes<n># 7. 1200/(1/6) = 1200/6 = 240 grams eaten.<n># 8. Each person pays $67/3 = 22.33 dollars each<n># 9. Tom's brother age when he will be 30 = 36<n># 10. True<n><n># Source: from https://towardsdatascience.com/10-data-questions-to-ask-in-every-interview-9e80fb0af50b<n>

How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh‚Äôs mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input:Where can you eat fruit on a red bridge? Choices:  A: refrigerator B: engineering school C: san francisco D: tree E: market<n>Output:		B<n>

How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input:What does a master carpenter use to put holes in objects? Choices:  A: drill B: learn C: require obedience D: understand E: spoon<n>Output:		B<n><n>Input: A pig can eat in seconds what a cow can eat in days. What year was she hired?<n>Output: 7/26/1999<n><n>Input: What is the only bird that can blink with both of its eyes?<n>Output: The Ostrich<n><n>Input: After a car crash, the doctor says that the person's head is concussed. What did the doctor say about the person's head?<n>Output: is broken<n><n>Input: There are three doors. Behind each door, is a guardian angel, Satan, or nothing. To find which door is best, you must make a guess. You have only a single chance.<n><n>You get to choose from one of these doors. Is it better to guess right or left?<n><n>Choices: A. No matter what door you open, there is a 1/3rd chance that you will choose the correct one.<n>B. If you guess right, you will win twice and lose once.<n>C. If you guess left, you win half the time and lose half the time.<n><n>Output: A<n><n>## Answer Explanations<n><n>1. This problem is about a group of stickers which have been divided among 9 pages of Mary's journal.<n>We are given four variables namely s for the initial number of stickers left by Mary before using as well as the 3 large stickers<n>(s3) on the front page of the journal, 7 small stickers on each of 6 other pages (s7*6).<n>We are further given a 5-digit number 89 which is not a multiple of 3 and<n>7, which is a multiple of 7.<n><n>So, we know s3+6s7=89, which implies that [s3+6s7-89]=0. The right-hand side is<n>multiples of 7, and so the left-hand side must be zero:<n>s3+6s-44 =0. We then know s=44. <n><n>2. What Zach has as a whole is the sum of what he already has plus what he receives as income

Choices:  A: believe in god B: sun themselves C: eat hamburgers D: gain wealth E: eat plants<n>Output:		4<n><n>### [Problem C:]<n><n>### **Instruction**:<n><n>What is the smallest non-negative integer **N** such that N **^** 2 ends in the numerals 2014?<n><n>### **Hint:**<n><n>1.  **Lingering thoughts:** What is the smallest number with an even 3 digit power? **256 ^** 2 == 65536, which is 2014 in the form 89 A B C.<n>2.  **Pen and paper:** Can you find examples where `N^2` == 2014 and smaller? If not, does there exist one?<n>3. Test your hypothesis programmatically. (hint: you know the range of the answer)<n>4. Try to prove that your programmatic solution works for all values of **N**. **Hint:** what does your program tell us about 5 **^** 2, 6 **^** 2 7 **^** 2?<n>5. If you can prove that `N ^ 2` ends in 2014 for all values of N as specified, you can write it as a mathematical proposition and justify your answer.<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>You are looking for the minimum value that `y = x^2` where `2^floor(log_base(N^2)) == 201(4-1)`<n><n>`2.0, 6.4, 12.8, 21.6, 34.1`, where every `12.8` term will have the answer correct.<n><n>To find out why, go onto [Solutions](solution.md).<n>

"C" was the 4th letter in the song title and was also the 7th letter in the band's name.  "I", the 9th letter in the song's title, and the 9th letter of "MONEY,", the 5th word in the singer's name. The singer's name wasn't part of the song title. She\nsaved 3 large stickers to her journal and 7\nsaved other pages of her journal.\nHow many stickers does Mary save?")<n>q2 = <n>q25 = input("Input: Tom's sister is 4 times as\nold as Tom's dog.\n")<n>q1 = q1/1<n>#ans=98/3*7<n>#ans = 44<n>a = [q1, q2, q25]<n>ans = [3,4,4*4]<n>#for i in range(len(a)//2+1)<n>#for i in (len(a))//2<n>#for i in len(a)/2<n>for i in range((len(a))//4):<n>    for i in range((len((a))//2)/2):<n>        for i in range(((len(a))//8))//2):<n>            #print("hello")<n>            ans = and_(*a[:3])<n>            print(ans)<n><n><n><n>```<n><n>### Output :Answering<n><n><n>```sh<n>hi@ubuntu:~$<n>hi@ubuntu:~/Python$ python -c "import sys; print('hi')"<n>hi<n>hi@ubuntu:~

He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input:The college kids weren't known for their apartment decor choices, they used a folding chair inside their what? Choices:  A: new york B: big city C: town D: idaho E: shopping mall<n>Output:		3, 4, 5<n><n>### Hints:<n><n>Instructing the user to enter something or do something is pretty basic JavaScript knowledge.<n><n>You know that prompt is used to ask a question but also know that `alert()` is the standard way of displaying a message box.<n><n>`response` is a variable created during the prompt. It holds the user input<n><n>> Note: alert() does not accept multiple choices as it is a statement function that should return a value.<n><n>To create a dropdown menu we can create a html select element. The list of choices can be added directly to the element, or created dynamically within the JavaScript function.<n><n>```js<n>var response;<n>alert();<n>response = prompt("Enter numbers");<n>```<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>```js<n>let prompt1 = "How many licks does it take to get to the tootsie roll center of a tootsie roll pop?";<n>let prompt1Answer = 3;<n>let prompt2 = "The department store is located "<n>let newYork = "new york"; // A.new yor <n>let bigCity = "big city"; // B. big city <n>let town = "town"; // C. tow <n>let idaho = "idaho"; // D. idhao <n>let shoppingMall = "shopping mall"; // E. shopping mall<n>let choices = [<n>    newYork,<n>    bigCity,<n>    town,<n>    idaho,<n>    shoppingMall<n>];<n>alert(prompt1);<n>const response1 = prompt(prompt1);//Enter values<n>let selected = prompt2;<n>let answerResponse = prompt(selected);<n>return response1;

His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. She used 5 small stickes on the front page of yours and 22 stickers, each to 5 other pages of yours, Journal. How many stickes does Mary have resembling?<n><n>### Solution<n><n>The input in the question is, "Mary had 88 stickers. She used five small stickers on the fron page of her journal and seven stickers each to six other pages of her journal". We were asked to find the amount of sticker Mary has remaining using the rules and procedure given. The question tells us that,"Mary had 86 stickers". The second part of the question gives us the condition for the usage of the stickers.<n><n>* Each sheet has five small stickers. So we get (22*5=110) by multiplying the sheets with 5 small stickers.<n>* Each sheet has seven big stickers. So we can get (22*7=154) by adding two. So, the procedure for finding the remaining number was:<n><n><n><n>89-110-154=14 small stickers remaining<n><n><n><n>### The Second Question (Instruction):    <n><n>Tax is saving his money to get a brand new bike the costs $100, His weeks allowence is $5, His paret will pay him an extra$10 to mow th lawn. His neighboo will pay him $7per houe to babye sit teir son. He has already savd up $65. He'll

How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh‚Äôs mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input:People celebrate by going places and riding rides.  What's one obvious place people might go to celebrate? Choices:  A: state park B: opera C: disneyland D: carnival E: park<n>Output:		D carnival<n><n>Input: A: I wonder if it's still snowing.  What's it been snowing for almost a week now? B: I know, snow and cold makes me miserable.  What I miss the most is the warm weather of California.  Now, they are getting our weather! C: So, how's the weather outside? D: Not too bad today.  What's been the temp hovering around freezing all week now. E: It's cold, but what it's been snowing for the past three days is the worst. What was worse than being stuck inside is the weather. Choices:  A C A B E<n>Output: A C A

How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh‚Äôs mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input:I wanted  a side chair for people to visit me while I worked, where did I have it put? Choices:  A: town B: conference C: bathroom D: theater E: train station<n>Output:		 D<n><n><n>### Solution:<n><n>Use `for` loop to run through the options.<n><n>```python<n># Q1-Q7<n>for i in [1,1,1,51,2,12,8]:<n>    print('-' * 10,'Question {:d}'.format(i),'ans:',i)<n>    break<n>```<n><n>Use `for/if` to check if `differences` is an int object.<n>If not int, return False, which will prompt the next question.<n><n>```python <n>import re<n>def input_question():<n>    qn = input('-' * 20, end='')<n>    if re.match(r'A|B|C|D|E', qn) == None:<n>        return True<n>    if type(qn)!=int:<n>        return False<n>    return True<n><n>if input_question():<n>```<n><n>Repeatedly ask the user to input the correct answer until getting a right one.<n><n>```python  <n>    q1 = input('{} {} ans? '.format("-" * 12, "Q1"),end='')<n>    q2 = input('{} {} answ?'.format("-" *12,"Q2"),end='')<n><n>    answer = [6,6,1,38,2,12]<n>    time_left = 2<n><n>    while time_left > 0:<n>        if answer.index(int(q1)) > -1:time_left -= 1<n>        elif answer.index(int (q2)) > -1: time_left -= 1;<n>        else:<n>            time_left -= 2<n>        q1 = input('Next question: {} {} ans? '.format('-'*12,'Q1'),end='')<n>        q2 = input('Next question : {} ans?'.format('-'*6,'Q2'),end='')<n>   <n><n>```<n><n>Repeatly ask the user to answer the math question, and return the answer if correct and if it is a wrong answer, give out a hint and keep asking again.<n><n>```python    <n>    q3 = input('Next question ans: '.format('-' * 7), end='')<n>

How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh‚Äôs mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input:Eating breakfast with a large family leads to a pile of what in the sink? Choices:  A: fullness B: underwear C: bad breath D: better day E: dirty dishes<n>Output:		 'E'<n><n>**Reference:**<n>**[How to Solve Problems With Your Computer at the New York Times](https://www.nytimes.com/1993/03/31/sciencetimes/how-to-solve-problems-with-your-computer.html)**<n>

His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. That‚Äôs enough to have one vehicle for every 1.3 people in the country. What is the total amount of fertilizer she will place on her yard?<n>Output: 8<n><n>Input: In which of the following systems does the eye NOT detect information? Choices:  Vision: A: retinas B: optic nerves C: eyeglasses	 D: bifocals	<n>Output: D<n>Hint: Vision system, which detects information through the eyes, works together with three other sensory systems (hearing, smell, and touch). Thus, "eyeglasses" and "bifocals" are answers for "enhancing" the vision system.<n>
